:: \ Karakov Lives {"position":"4300,1100","size":"100,100"}
The room settles faster than it should.

Guards move into position with practiced ease. No shouting. No confusion. Just discipline snapping back into place.

Karakov steps forward.

He looks at the fallen gun on the floor, then at you, then at Thomas.

There is no anger in his expression.

Only clarity.

Karakov:
You disappoint me.

He gestures once. The guards stop.

Karakov reaches down and picks up his weapon himself. He checks the chamber, adjusts his grip — unhurried, instructional, as if showing how it should have been done.

He meets Thomas’s eyes first.

Karakov:
You should have known better.

A shot rings out.

Thomas collapses without a sound.

The world narrows. Your ears ring. Your body refuses to move.

Karakov turns to you.

For the first time, he steps close enough that you can smell the oil on his gloves.

Karakov:
Wars aren’t ended by conviction.
They’re ended by those who don’t hesitate.

He raises the gun.

There is no dramatic pause.
No last words.

Just a final correction.


