:: \ Karakov Wrong way {"position":"3200,800","size":"100,100"}
You speak first.

The words leave your mouth cleanly. Correct. Respectful.

For a fraction of a second, nothing happens.

(text-colour:red)[Karakov] stops.

Slowly, he turns to face you—not surprised, just mildly curious. His eyes move over you, measured, like he’s confirming a detail he already knew.

The smile comes a moment later.

(text-colour:red)[Karakov]: Ah. Eager.

He steps closer—not into your space, but close enough that you feel the adjustment.

(text-colour:red)[Karakov]: You’ll forgive me if I don’t return the greeting.
When I enter a room, it’s usually better to let the room decide what it wants to say.

A soft pause.

(text-colour:red)[Karakov]: Still… confidence is a useful flaw.

